       <subsection xml:id="Question4_2_17">
    <title> Problem 17</title>
<p>
    Keep in mind that I did this problem on paper first and am presenting it in a "cleaned up" form.
    
</p>
<p>
    Since <m>b \equiv d \pmod{n}</m>, <m>n|b-d</m> and so <md>
        d=b-nk
    </md> for some integer <m>k.</m>
    Since <m>ab \equiv cd \pmod{n}</m>, 
    <md>
        <mrow> \amp  n|ab-cd </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp n| ab-c(b-nk)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp n|ab-cb+cnk.</mrow>
    </md>
Since <m>n|cnk</m> we have
<md>
    <mrow> \amp n|ab-cb</mrow>
    <mrow> \amp n|b(a-c)</mrow>.
</md>
Finally, since <m>\text{gcd}(n,b)=1</m> we have <md>
    n|a-c
</md>
by Euclid's lemma.  That is, <m>a\equiv c \pmod{n}.</m>

    
</p>
</subsection>

     <subsection xml:id="Question4_2_18">
    <title> Problem 18</title>
<p>
    We have:
    <md>
        <mrow>\amp n_1|a-b  </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp n_2|a-c.</mrow>
    </md>
    Let <m>\text{gcd}(n_1,n_2)=n</m>, then 
    <md number="yes">
        <mrow> \amp n|a-b</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp n|a-c</mrow>
    </md>
    So, <md>
        <mrow> \amp n|(a-b)-(a-c)</mrow>    
        <mrow> \amp n|c-b .</mrow>
    </md>
    That is, <m>c\equiv b \pmod{n}.</m>
</p>
     </subsection>
